Introduction ¶

This notebook contains all the code neccessary to make the thymio robot navigating in the environnement that we conceive. There are 4 modules built in classes :

  • One for the computer vision which takes the input of the camera and hands the map and the estimated position and angle of the robot to the other parts
  • One for the computation of the path in which we use the A* algorithm
  • One for the Kalman filter which estimates the position and orientation of the robot on the map during all its path to the defined goal
  • One for the local navigation and control motion which takes the path computed by the A* algorithm, the estimated position as well as the input of the horizontal proximity sensors and set the motors wheel to the speed that will make them reach the goal
  • One module which is called robot and make all of these modules comunicate with each other. It has also a main loop that we can launch in order for the robot to reach the goal

Those modules are in .py files in the folder handled and are imported in this notebook.

Environment ¶

For our project we choose the environment as follows:

  • Corner marks: We use the same patterns on the corner of QR code as our corner marks. These marks are placed on three of four vertices of a rectangle to mark the boundary of the arena.
  • Arena: The area in which the robot moves. The arena is a $1.5m \times 1m$ rectangle on flat, light colored terrain. The rectangle is defined by the corner marks mentioned above.
  • Obstacles: Anything that is dark colored can be placed in the arena as obstacles to be taken into consideration in global navigation. Objects high enough to be detected by the proximity sensors on Thymio can be placed as obstacles to test local navigation while the robot is running.
  • Start point: The initial position of robot.
  • Goal point: Goal point is marked as the center on the line connecting the centers of two black circles on paper.
  • Camera position: Camera is mounted on the wall, roughly 1.9m above the ground. Camera orientation should be adjusted so that its view covers the whole arena. It's not necessary to keep the optical axis of the camera perpendicular to the arena surface (ground).

Computer vision module ¶

The computer vision module takes the picture shot by the camera as input, and is resiponsible for outputing occupancy grid map, getting goal position, and estimating the pose of robot from the picture using CV approaches.

Image Affine Transformation ¶

To ease the need of mount the camera on the top right of the arena, we place corner marks on the corners of the arena and get the affine matrix by matching the triangle's dimensions in reality and in the image.

The pipeline is shown in flow chart below. We first convert the original RGB image to Gray scale image, then binarize the gray image to get binary image with only black and white pixels. This binary image usually contains many dark dots and jagged edges, which cause extra computational burden for edge detection and interfere with mapping process. So we apply morpholocal open operation on the binarized image to filter out the dots and smooth the edges.

Subsequently, to locate the corner marks, we run edge detection algorighm findcontours to first find all contours. Each corner mark consists of 3 square contours of different sizes sequentially circumscribing smaller one, so we can traverse all the contours to only filter contours by their hierarchy information, and then we can get the position of the vertices of one triangle in image coordinates.

Since we appoint the dimensions of the arena to be $1.5m \times 1m$ (other dimensions will also work), we can calculate to get the affine matrix. This affine matrix is capable to transform the original image to top view of the arena, in which the ground plane is parallel to the image plane.

Mapping ¶

The arena is light colored, and we place dark colored objects in the arena as obstacles to be taken into consideration in global navigation.

We apply affine transformation on the binarized image, and resize it to reasonable size, which in our case is 33 $\times$ 50. We do this because the number of grids will greatly impact the speed of A* search.

Since the location is designed to get the coordinates of the center of the robot, and robot has its radius, so it is necessary to expand the coverage of obstacles in map. In this way we can also increase the safe distance between robot and obstacles, which makes it more robust to localization error. We do this by apply mophological erode operation on the affined binarized image. The impact of dark parts on robot and the goal mark will be compensated. The resulted image consists of only black and white pixels will serve as occupancy grid map.

Localization ¶

CV module estimates the pose of the robot by thresholding in HSV color space. We designed the robot localization mark to be a red rectangle on the front and a blue rectangle on the back. By thresholding in HSV color space we can filter out pixels of corresponding color and compute their momentum to get the mass center of these two colors. The x, y coordinates is given by the mean of the two centers and orientation is given by compute the angle of the vector pointing to red center mass from blue center mass.

Goal Point Detection ¶

CV module estimates the position of goal point by Hough circle detection. We designed the goal mark to be two circles of different sizes. The x, y coordinates is given by the mean of the centers of detected circles.

Visualization ¶

In addition to the debug images mentioned above, we have an consistently updating image monitor.png to visualize the current status of the whole system. Here are the meanings of grids of different color:

  • Black: traversable space.
  • White: space occupied by obstacles or corner markers, untraversable.
  • Green: pose estimation given by observation using the camera.
  • Red: pose estimation filtered by Extended Kalman Filter.
  • Blue: global path planned. Note that obstacle used for testing local navigation won't be detected.

A* algorithm ¶

The Global Navigation module is used at the beginning of the execution to compute the path the robot needs to follow to the goal position. We decided to use A* as algorithm since it returns an optimal solution and it is easy to implement. The main drawback that prevents the usage of it for large applications is the high computational cost, but our map is very small and the path only needs to be computed once, so it is not a problem.

The module takes as input the map and the start and goal position, and returns the optimal path between the two positions.

The map is an array of 0 and 1, that represents respectively free and blocked passages. The Astar function returns the shortest path as a vector of positions in the map.

The map is an array so movements can only be either vertical, horizontal or diagonal, so the turning angle is limited to 45. Thus to obtain a smooth movement of the robot it is necessary to smoothen the path in local navigation.

Part of the implementation is taken from the lab about global navigation, adapted to interface with the rest of the code. To run the algorithm the function Astar is called, this makes the link between the map provided by the vision module and the function A_Star that actually computes the A* algorithm.

Kalman filter ¶

The objective of Filtering is to get a precise estimation of the position, despite noisy data from the sensors of the robots and the environment.

The easiest form of filtering is a Kalman Filter, which works well as long as the estimation of the position can be approximated as a gaussian distribution.

For our application, the position can be approximated using a Gaussian, as long as for small period of times before the real distribution takes the typical banana shape, and given the assumption that the robot moves continuously (without kidnappings) in space. The technique still manages to handle kidnapping, but it takes more time than other algorithms to recover from a kidnap.

The filtering process is composed of two separate phases:

Estimation Phase ¶

We want to estimate the position given the current position by integrating the movement of the robot. This process can be achieve using the internal IMU sensors (accelerometer and gyroscope), or the speed sensors of the robot wheels.

We decided to use the speed sensors, since the robot has a small inertia, accelerations are very fast and the robot travels at constant speed the majority of the time.

Given the speed of the left and right wheel, we can compute v and $\omega$, by applying the linear transformation:

$$ v = \frac{v_L + v_R}{2} \newline \omega = \frac{v_L - v_R}{b} $$

Then from v and $\omega$, the updated position can be computed by applying the transformation:

$$ x_{k+1} = x_k + v \delta t \cos(\theta_k) \newline y_{k+1} = y_k + v \delta t \sin(\theta_k) \newline \theta_{k+1} = \theta_k + \omega \delta t $$

Putting it all together, given the previous position and the speed of the motor, we can compute the estimation of the new position with the matrix product:

$$ \begin{bmatrix} \mu_{x_{k+1}} \\ \mu_{y_{k+1}} \\ \mu_{\theta_{k+1}} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \mu_{x_{k}} \\ \mu_{y_{k}} \\ \mu_{\theta_{k}} \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta_k) & 0 \\ \sin(\theta_k) & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \frac 12 & \frac 12 \\ \frac 1b & -\frac 1b \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} v_L \\ v_R \end{bmatrix} \delta t $$

The second matrix can be computed offline, while the first is a non linear function so it needs to be computed online for the current position at every cycle.

The estimation phase increases the uncertainty of the prediction, as sampling and integrating noises causes the robot to diverge overtime.

We can consider the increase of the uncertainty as constant over time, so defined the parameter Q, the variance can be updated using the formula:

$$ \Sigma_{k+1} = \Sigma_k + Q \delta t $$

Measurement Phase ¶

We want to use the data coming from the camera to decrease the uncertainty of the position, also the measurement of the position can be unprecise, so it does not bring variance to zero but only decreases it.

Given the measured position y and the current prediction $\mu$ of $(x,y,\theta)$, the steps required are:

  • Compute the innovation $i = y_{measure} - \mu_{current} C$.
  • Compute the optimal gain for the correction $K = \Sigma C^T (C\Sigma C^T + R)^{-1}$.
  • Update the mean of the prediction $\mu_{k+1} = \mu_k + Ki$.
  • Update the covariance matrix $\Sigma_{k+1} = (I - KC) \Sigma_k$.

An important detail of the implementation is the calibration and the setting of parameters, for the calibration we care to know the distance the robot can move given the speed and the time delay.

The easiest technique is to measure a pure $\omega$ with $v_L+v_R = 0$, since the number k of $2\pi$ rotations can be easily computed. Then fixing b the distance between the wheels in number cm (it then needs to be adapted given the size of a map tile), the moltiplicative factor can be calculated as $C = \frac{2 \pi k t b}{v_L-v_R}$.

Testing different values of parameters for Q, C and R allows to get good results for the filtering process.

Local navigation and control motion ¶

The objective of local navigation and motion control is to follow the path provided by the global navigation algorithm, smoothing the very sharp angles of the A* algorithms.

To achieve this goal a PD controller to set $\omega$ can be adopted. After computing the next position to reach in the map, we calculate the difference between the current orientation of the robot and the orientation needed to reach the next goal position, then an angular velocity $\omega = k \delta \theta$ proportional to this difference between the two angles is set. Higher values of k make the robot less smooth but more precise to follow the trajectory, on the other hand lower values make the robot smoother but also less responsive.

The right value of k depends on multiple factors: the size of the obstacles in the map, the speed of the robot. Another important factor to also consider is the satisfaction of the local obstacle avoidance, the robot doesn't have sensors on the side, so it is crucial to not bump back into avoided obstacles when the sensors can no longer sense them. With lower values of k, it takes longer for the robot to go back on the path so it is less probable to bump into obstacle on the way.

Another important detail to keep into consideration is the update of the point to follow. Requiring the robot to reach the exact goal before moving to the following can be faulty, as a local obstacle may be on the point, or generally imprecise navigation may lead the robot to just turn around it.

To avoid this problem a solution is to move to the next point when the distance is less than a certain threshold.

Higher values of the threshold make the robot smoothen the trajectory, but also cause it to cut curves with obstacles. This problem can be solved with local obstacle avoidance, since the robot senses the obstacle and prevent from bumping into it.

The algorithm to find the next point works by computing the minimum distance from the robot position to the path, then moving N additional steps until the distance is greater than the threshold.

Local avoidance ¶

The objective of local obstacle avoidance is to avoid local obstacle not present on the map that the robot may encounter on his path. This is crucial since the alternative of recomputing the map and the path every time a new obstacle is in the way is too time consuming, energy inefficient and sometimes unfeasible. In fact it is generally hard to recompute a big map, and local obstacles are ever changing.

The local navigation implementation is very simple. It localize the local obstacle in front of the robot, computes his direction, and deviates to avoid it.

This is obtained in practice by finding the sensor that has the lowest distance (biggest value) from the obstacle using the proximity sensors, computing whether the object is on the front left or on the front right of the robot, and turning in the opposite direction with a fixed angular speed $\omega_{avoid}$.

Robot module ¶

The whole system needs to be integrated, and the different components need to be correctly run alternatively to ensure the correct functioning of the robot. It is therefore important for the execution of the online components to run in a short time, to ensure a good responsiveness of the system to local obstacles and a smooth navigation.

The execution order of the different modules can be syntesized with the diagram:

The first step is the computation of the map and the start and goal position in the vision module, followed by the kalman filter initialization and the global planning.

The main feedback loop is composed of the measurement of the current position from the camera, the filtering of the position given the motor speed sensors and the measured position, and the local navigation and obstacle avoidance given the filtered position and the path to follow.

The function to be called to start the execution of the software is complete_execution(), it establishes the connection to the Thymio Robot, creates the Robot object and starts the main loop.

Result ¶

Through repeated experiment, it is demonstrated that:

  • The robot can perform path planning, path tracking and local obstacle avoidance successfully.
  • The robot can handle situation of being kidnapped. While the robot is running, we can grab it and place it elsewhere in the arena. The robot can orient itself and return to the planned path successfully. This is thanks to the measurements from the camera that incrementally correct the position.
  • The robot can run normally despite short camera measurements loss. If we block the camera from seeing the arena for some seconds, the robot can still estimate his position and follow the path precisely enough using only the robot data.
